  Introduction

Backstage is a platform that helps bring all development-related tools, services, and documentation into one place. Instead of using multiple tools separately, it provides a single interface where teams can manage everything related to software development.

As organizations grow, they usually end up with many services, tools, and repositories. Over time, it becomes difficult to track what services exist, who owns them, where the code is located, and how everything is connected. This leads to confusion, delays, and dependency on individuals for information.

Backstage is designed to solve this problem by acting as a central platform for developers. It organizes services, documentation, and tools in a structured way, making it easier for teams to find information and work efficiently.

It is not just a tool, but a platform that connects existing systems and provides a unified experience for development teams.


  🟢 Section 2: Objective of This Evaluation (Raw Content)

Objective of This Evaluation

The purpose of this evaluation is to understand whether Backstage can be used as a central platform to manage our development ecosystem more effectively.

Currently, we are using multiple tools and platforms to manage code, deployments, monitoring, and security. These tools work well individually, but they are not connected in a single place, which makes it difficult to get a complete view of our systems.

With the planned migration from Azure DevOps to GitHub, this is a good opportunity to evaluate whether Backstage can help us standardize our processes and improve visibility across all services and teams.

This evaluation aims to explore how Backstage can:

Provide a single view of all services and repositories
Improve visibility of ownership and responsibilities
Simplify access to documentation and tools
Support our existing and future workflows

The goal is not to replace existing tools, but to see how Backstage can integrate with them and bring everything together into one unified platform.




  Current Challenges

In the current setup, we are managing a large number of services, repositories, and tools across multiple workstreams. While each tool serves its purpose, there is no single place where everything is connected and easily accessible.

We have multiple workstreams, each with its own repository, and each repository contains several services. As the number of services grows, it becomes difficult to track all components effectively.

Some of the key challenges include:

Difficulty in identifying all available services across workstreams
Lack of clear visibility on service ownership and responsibilities
Documentation is spread across different locations and is not always easy to find
Developers need to switch between multiple tools for code, deployments, monitoring, and security
No centralized view to understand how services are connected or dependent on each other
Onboarding new team members takes more time due to scattered information

In addition to this, we are using different tools for different purposes such as code management, monitoring, and security scanning. Since these tools are not unified, it requires extra effort to gather complete information about a service.

Overall, the current setup works, but it lacks a centralized system that provides a clear and consistent view of the entire development ecosystem.

In addition to the existing challenges, current AI-based tools help mainly at a technical level but do not provide complete context.

For example, tools like GitHub Copilot can analyze repositories and explain the technical aspects such as code structure, dependencies, and functionality. However, they do not provide information about service ownership, business context, or how a service fits into a larger system or workstream.

This means developers may still need to rely on multiple sources or individuals to understand the complete picture of a service, especially from a business or organizational perspective.

There is currently no unified system that combines both technical insights and organizational context in one place.

In some cases, shared configurations are used to access systems such as Kubernetes clusters. When multiple users operate using the same configuration, it becomes difficult to track who performed a specific action. This lack of user-level visibility can lead to challenges in auditing and accountability.



  Overview of Backstage

Backstage is a platform that provides a single place to manage all development-related activities. It acts as a central dashboard where developers can access services, repositories, documentation, and tools without switching between multiple systems.

Instead of replacing existing tools, Backstage connects them and presents the information in a unified way. This helps teams work more efficiently by reducing the need to search across different platforms.

At the center of Backstage is the concept of a software catalog. This catalog maintains a structured list of all services, along with details such as ownership, dependencies, and related resources. This makes it easier to understand how different services are connected and who is responsible for them.

Backstage also provides a way to standardize development practices. It allows teams to create new services using predefined templates, ensuring consistency across projects. Documentation is managed alongside the code, making it easier to maintain and access.

Another important aspect of Backstage is its ability to integrate with various tools such as code repositories, deployment platforms, monitoring systems, and security tools. These integrations allow developers to view all relevant information about a service in one place.

Overall, Backstage simplifies the development experience by organizing tools, services, and information into a single, easy-to-use platform.


  Key Features and Capabilities

Backstage provides a set of features that help organize and simplify the software development process. These features are designed to improve visibility, standardization, and ease of access across all services and tools.

Software Catalog
The software catalog acts as a central place to store information about all services. It provides details such as service name, owner, repository, dependencies, and related resources. This helps teams quickly understand what services exist and who is responsible for them.

Software Templates
Backstage provides templates to create new services in a standardized way. Instead of setting up everything manually, developers can use predefined templates that follow best practices. This ensures consistency across all projects.

TechDocs (Documentation)
Backstage allows documentation to be written and maintained along with the code. This makes it easier to keep documentation up to date and ensures it is always available in one place.

Search
The search feature helps users quickly find services, documentation, APIs, and other resources. It reduces the time spent looking for information across different tools.

Permissions and Access Control
Backstage allows organizations to control access to services and data. Different users can be given different levels of access based on their roles.

Kubernetes Visibility
Backstage provides visibility into the health and status of services running in Kubernetes. Developers can check whether their services are running properly without switching to separate tools.

Plugins and Integrations
Backstage supports a wide range of plugins to integrate with different tools such as code repositories, monitoring systems, Kubernetes, and security platforms. There are many pre-built plugins available, and based on requirements, additional plugins can be integrated.

If a required integration is not available, custom plugins can be developed to extend Backstage functionality and connect with internal or external systems.
Tech Radar
Backstage provides a Tech Radar feature that helps teams understand which technologies, tools, and frameworks are being used across the organization. It can categorize technologies into groups such as adopt, trial, or hold. This helps developers make informed decisions and align with recommended technologies.
  
🟢 Section 6: How Backstage Works (High-Level) (Raw Content)

How Backstage Works (High-Level)

Backstage works as a central platform that connects different tools and services and displays them in a single interface.

At a high level, it has three main parts:

User Interface (Frontend)
This is what developers interact with. It provides a dashboard where users can view services, check documentation, monitor systems, and access different tools in one place.

Backend Services
The backend is responsible for collecting information from different tools and systems. It connects to repositories, monitoring tools, deployment platforms, and other services, and brings that data into Backstage.

Plugins (Integrations)
Plugins are used to connect Backstage with external tools. Each plugin is responsible for integrating a specific tool or functionality, such as code repositories, Kubernetes, monitoring systems, or security tools.

These plugins allow Backstage to gather and display information from multiple sources without replacing the tools themselves.

Overall, Backstage acts as a layer on top of existing systems. It connects different tools and presents all the relevant information in a single, unified view, making it easier for developers to work efficiently.


🟢 Section 7: Mapping to Our Current Ecosystem (Raw Content)

Mapping to Our Current Ecosystem

In our current setup, we are using multiple tools and platforms to manage different aspects of the development lifecycle. While each tool works effectively on its own, there is no single place where all information is connected and easily accessible.

Backstage can act as a central platform to integrate these tools and provide a unified view of our entire ecosystem.

Code Management and CI/CD
We are currently using Azure DevOps and planning to migrate to GitHub for repository management and pipelines. Backstage can integrate with GitHub to provide visibility into repositories, pull requests, and workflows, all within a single interface.

Microservices Architecture
We have multiple workstreams, each containing its own repository with multiple services. In total, we have a large number of microservices across the organization. Backstage can organize all these services in a structured catalog, making it easier to track, search, and manage them.

Kubernetes (AKS)
Our services are deployed on Kubernetes using AKS. Backstage can integrate with Kubernetes to show the health and status of services, allowing developers to monitor their applications without switching platforms.

Monitoring (Prometheus and Grafana)
We use monitoring tools to track system performance and metrics. Backstage can bring these insights into a single view by linking dashboards and metrics directly to the corresponding services.

Code Quality and Security (SonarQube, Snyk)
We are using tools for code quality and security scanning. Backstage can integrate these tools to display code quality metrics and vulnerability information alongside each service.

Workstream Structure
Each workstream has its own repository and multiple services. Backstage can help organize services based on domains, systems, or teams, making it easier to understand how services are grouped and how they relate to each other.

Overall, Backstage can connect all these tools and services into a single platform, providing better visibility, easier navigation, and improved understanding of the entire system.

🟢 Section 8: Expected Benefits (Raw Content)

Expected Benefits

By adopting Backstage, we can expect improvements in visibility, efficiency, and standardization across our development ecosystem. It helps different teams work more effectively by providing a single platform to access all relevant information.

For Developers
Developers can easily find information about services, including ownership, documentation, and dependencies. This reduces the time spent searching across multiple tools and helps them focus more on development work. It also simplifies onboarding for new team members by providing a clear view of the system.

For Engineering Managers
Managers gain better visibility into all services, teams, and ownership. This helps in tracking progress, maintaining standards, and ensuring consistency across different workstreams. It also makes it easier to manage large and complex systems.

For Platform and DevOps Teams
Platform teams can standardize how services are created and managed using templates. They can also integrate multiple tools into one platform, reducing complexity and improving overall system organization.

Improved Visibility
All services, tools, and documentation are available in one place. This makes it easier to understand how different parts of the system are connected.

Standardization
Using templates and structured organization, Backstage helps ensure that all services follow common standards and best practices.

Reduced Tool Switching
Developers no longer need to move between multiple tools to gather information. Everything is accessible through a single interface.

Faster Onboarding
New team members can quickly understand the system, services, and ownership without relying heavily on others.

Overall, Backstage improves the development experience by making information easily accessible and reducing complexity in managing large systems.
Improved Access Control and Traceability
With integration to identity providers such as GitHub or Azure Active Directory, each user accesses Backstage using their own credentials. This helps in controlling access and improves traceability of actions, unlike shared configurations where user-level tracking is not possible.

  🟢 Section 9: Demo Scope and Walkthrough (Raw Content)

Demo Scope and Walkthrough

The purpose of the demo is to show how Backstage can provide a centralized view of services, tools, and documentation, and how it simplifies the development experience.

The demo will focus on a few key scenarios to demonstrate the capabilities of Backstage in a practical way.

Service Catalog View
Show how all services are listed in one place using the software catalog. Demonstrate how a user can view service details such as ownership, repository, and related information.

Service Details Page
Open a specific service and show how all relevant information is available in one place. This may include links to code repositories, documentation, monitoring dashboards, and other integrations.

Creating a New Service Using Templates
Demonstrate how a new service can be created using predefined templates. This will show how Backstage helps standardize service creation and reduces manual effort.

Documentation Access (TechDocs)
Show how documentation is stored and accessed within Backstage. Highlight how documentation is linked to services and easy to find.

Kubernetes Visibility
Demonstrate how service health and deployment status can be viewed directly within Backstage without switching to another tool.

Search Functionality
Show how users can quickly search for services, documentation, or other resources.

Integration View
Highlight how different tools such as code repositories, monitoring, and security tools are connected and accessible from a single platform.

Overall, the demo will focus on showing how Backstage brings together multiple tools and services into a unified and easy-to-use interface.



  🟢 Section 10: Limitations and Considerations (Raw Content)

Limitations and Considerations

While Backstage provides many benefits, there are certain considerations and efforts required before adopting it in a production environment.

Initial Setup Effort
Setting up Backstage requires time and effort, especially when integrating multiple tools and services. It is not a plug-and-play solution and needs proper configuration.

Customization Requirement
To fully match our organization’s needs, Backstage may require customization. This includes defining service structures, ownership models, and integrating internal tools.

Data and Metadata Management
Backstage relies on accurate service information such as ownership, dependencies, and documentation. Maintaining this data consistently across all services requires discipline and proper processes.

Integration Effort
Although Backstage supports many integrations, connecting all tools (such as monitoring, security, and CI/CD systems) may require additional setup and configuration.

Learning Curve
Teams may need time to understand how to use Backstage effectively. Proper onboarding and guidance will be required.

Migration Considerations
As we are planning to move from Azure DevOps to GitHub, integration and alignment with new workflows need to be carefully managed along with Backstage adoption.

Ongoing Maintenance
Backstage is not a one-time setup. It requires continuous updates, plugin management, and improvements to keep it aligned with evolving needs.
Custom Plugin Development Effort
While many plugins are available, some integrations may require custom plugin development. This requires additional effort and understanding of the Backstage framework.

Overall, while Backstage offers strong capabilities, it requires proper planning, setup, and ongoing effort to achieve maximum value.


🟢 Section 11: Future Possibilities (Raw Content)

Future Possibilities

Backstage not only helps in organizing the current development ecosystem, but also opens up possibilities for future improvements and advanced capabilities.

One of the key areas of future enhancement is the integration of AI with Backstage to provide more intelligent and context-aware insights.

Currently, AI tools can help analyze code and explain technical details of a repository. However, they do not provide complete context such as service ownership, business purpose, or how a service fits into a larger system.

With Backstage acting as a centralized platform that contains structured information about services, ownership, and relationships, it becomes possible to combine this data with AI capabilities.

This can enable use cases such as:

Providing both technical and business-level explanations of services
Identifying service ownership and responsible teams automatically
Understanding dependencies between services across different workstreams
Assisting developers with context-aware suggestions based on the system structure
Reducing dependency on manual documentation or individual knowledge

By integrating AI with Backstage, we can move towards a more intelligent platform where developers not only access information but also receive meaningful insights and guidance.

In the future, this can help improve decision-making, reduce effort in understanding systems, and enhance overall productivity.


  🟢 Section 12: Conclusion (Raw Content)

Conclusion

Backstage provides a centralized platform to bring together services, tools, and documentation into a single, unified interface. It helps address common challenges in managing large and complex development environments by improving visibility, organization, and accessibility.

Based on the evaluation, Backstage appears to be a suitable solution for environments with multiple services, tools, and workstreams. It aligns well with our current setup and the planned transition to GitHub, offering an opportunity to standardize and simplify our development processes.

While there are some considerations such as setup effort, customization, and ongoing maintenance, the overall benefits in terms of improved developer experience, better visibility, and system organization make it a strong candidate for further exploration.

This evaluation helps in understanding how Backstage can fit into our ecosystem and provides a foundation for deciding the next steps towards implementation.
  
